  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- Initial focus on financial institutions reporting suspicious transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Creation of global anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Increased international collaboration and information sharing\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (2002) in UK\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded scope of reporting requirements\n- Stricter customer due diligence regulations\n- Enhanced penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Cryptocurrency transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced digital forensic capabilities\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Broader definition of financial crimes\n- More comprehensive risk-based approaches\n\n6. Global Regulatory Frameworks\n- Continuous updates to FATF recommendations\n- Harmonization of international AML standards\n- Increased scrutiny of cross-border transactions\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve in response to emerging financial technologies and sophisticated criminal techniques.",
